  "topic_name": "States of Matter",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Matter exists in three main states: solid, liquid, and gas. In solids, particles are tightly packed and vibrate in fixed positions, giving solids a definite shape and volume. In liquids, particles are less tightly packed and can slide past each other, so liquids have a definite volume but take the shape of their container. In gases, particles are far apart and move freely, so gases have neither definite shape nor definite volume. Matter can change from one state to another by gaining or losing heat energy. These changes include melting, freezing, evaporation, boiling, condensation, and sublimation.",
    "rules": [
      "Solids have definite shape and definite volume",
      "Liquids have definite volume but no definite shape",
      "Gases have neither definite shape nor definite volume",
      "Melting: solid to liquid (requires heat)",
      "Freezing: liquid to solid (releases heat)",
      "Evaporation: liquid to gas at any temperature",
      "Boiling: liquid to gas at boiling point",
      "Condensation: gas to liquid (releases heat)",
      "Sublimation: solid directly to gas",
      "Heating increases particle motion and may cause change of state"
    ]
  },
